1
00:02:44,414 --> 00:02:46,500
[birds chirping]

2
00:02:46,541 --> 00:02:48,335
[vehicle approaching]

3
00:02:48,376 --> 00:02:49,795
[speaking French]

4
00:02:49,837 --> 00:02:51,212
The usurper.

5
00:02:53,090 --> 00:02:55,342
[woman speaking English]
Caro? He's here.

6
00:03:16,071 --> 00:03:18,281
-Professor Perlman.
-Welcome, welcome.

7
00:03:18,323 --> 00:03:20,450
-Thank you so much
for having me.
-Oh, my goodness.

8
00:03:20,492 --> 00:03:22,201
You're bigger
than your picture.

9
00:03:22,243 --> 00:03:23,578
Well, I couldn't get
all of me in the photo.
That's the problem.

10
00:03:23,620 --> 00:03:24,746
[laughing]

11
00:03:24,788 --> 00:03:25,873
[speaking other language]

12
00:03:25,914 --> 00:03:27,374
He seems very confident.

13
00:03:28,167 --> 00:03:29,793
-Mrs. Perlman.
-Annella.

14
00:03:29,835 --> 00:03:31,170
[speaking English]
Oliver. Very nice
to meet you.

15
00:03:31,210 --> 00:03:32,295
-Thank you for having
me in your home.
-Welcome.

16
00:03:32,337 --> 00:03:33,672
[speaking other langugae]
Where's Elio?

17
00:03:34,381 --> 00:03:35,549
I'll go down.

18
00:03:35,590 --> 00:03:37,425
[Perlman] Elio?

19
00:03:37,467 --> 00:03:39,636
-[speaking English]
You must be exhausted.
-[Oliver] What gave me away?

20
00:03:48,269 --> 00:03:49,855
[indistinct chatter]

21
00:03:51,940 --> 00:03:53,483
Hey. [in French]

22
00:03:53,525 --> 00:03:55,569
Darling, come help
Oliver take his things
up to his room.

23
00:03:55,610 --> 00:03:57,779
-He's already here?
-Yes!

24
00:03:57,821 --> 00:04:00,323
[Perlman speaking English]
Every single one
of these will.

25
00:04:00,365 --> 00:04:02,283
Elio, Oliver.
Oliver, Elio.

26
00:04:02,325 --> 00:04:04,119
-How you doing?
-Nice to meet you. Elio.

27
00:04:04,161 --> 00:04:05,913
[Perlman] You must
be exhausted.

28
00:04:05,954 --> 00:04:08,123
-A little bit.
-Come, come, come.

29
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:09,791
May I bring your things
up to your room?

30
00:04:09,833 --> 00:04:12,293
-Uh, sure. Yeah.
-My room?

31
00:04:12,335 --> 00:04:14,337
[Perlman laughs]

32
00:04:14,379 --> 00:04:16,131
Follow him.

33
00:04:16,173 --> 00:04:18,466
-You're very
welcome here.
-Si.

34
00:04:18,508 --> 00:04:20,468
Our home is your home.

35
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:21,636
[both blowing]

36
00:04:26,641 --> 00:04:28,018
[speaking other language]
You're leaving?

37
00:04:28,060 --> 00:04:30,104
-Hello.
-Hi.

38
00:04:31,980 --> 00:04:33,065
Nice to meet you.

39
00:04:42,574 --> 00:04:43,825
[door bangs shut]

40
00:04:46,828 --> 00:04:47,871
Oh.

41
00:04:59,340 --> 00:05:01,760
[speaking English]
My room is now your room.

42
00:05:01,802 --> 00:05:03,095
I'll be next door.

43
00:05:07,224 --> 00:05:09,309
We have to share
the bathroom.

44
00:05:10,602 --> 00:05:12,187
It's my only way out.

45
00:05:12,229 --> 00:05:13,521
[snoring]

46
00:05:34,584 --> 00:05:36,503
[piano music playing faintly]

47
00:05:49,308 --> 00:05:50,892
[bell ringing]

48
00:05:53,352 --> 00:05:55,189
[bell ringing in distance]

49
00:06:03,197 --> 00:06:05,364
We're being
called for dinner.

50
00:06:14,749 --> 00:06:16,251
[knocking on door]

51
00:06:33,935 --> 00:06:35,562
[snoring]

52
00:06:43,778 --> 00:06:45,197
[gasping]

53
00:06:47,157 --> 00:06:48,533
Sorry.

54
00:06:50,285 --> 00:06:51,494
Yeah.

55
00:06:51,536 --> 00:06:53,205
We're being
called for dinner.

56
00:06:53,247 --> 00:06:56,917
Oh, yeah, I'm probably
gonna pass.

57
00:06:56,958 --> 00:06:59,627
Will you make
an excuse for me
to your mom, though?

58
00:07:01,755 --> 00:07:03,548
Thanks, man.

59
00:07:06,176 --> 00:07:07,719
So, this is your
old room, huh?

60
00:07:10,389 --> 00:07:11,514
Thanks.

61
00:07:13,558 --> 00:07:14,642
Later.

62
00:07:22,150 --> 00:07:23,442
[door closing]

63
00:08:02,774 --> 00:08:04,483
[speaking other language]
I'll take care of the tart.

64
00:08:07,612 --> 00:08:10,073
-[speaking English] Ah.
-Wow. Look at this.

65
00:08:10,115 --> 00:08:11,241
Good morning, Professor.

66
00:08:11,283 --> 00:08:12,575
-Good morning.
-Back from the dead.

67
00:08:12,617 --> 00:08:14,953
-Was I out that long?
-It seemed like it, huh?

68
00:08:14,995 --> 00:08:17,331
-How are you?
-I... Well, rested now.

69
00:08:17,372 --> 00:08:18,873
-Thank you.
-I'm glad.

70
00:08:18,915 --> 00:08:20,250
Would you like
some espresso?

71
00:08:20,292 --> 00:08:22,585
[Oliver] I would love some.
Thank you very much.

72
00:08:22,627 --> 00:08:25,172
This looks amazing.
I didn't take your
seat, did I?

73
00:08:25,213 --> 00:08:27,799
Oh, no, no, no.
It's okay. Please.

74
00:08:27,841 --> 00:08:29,676
Did you...
Did you recover
from your trip?

75
00:08:29,717 --> 00:08:31,052
I did. Yeah, big time.

76
00:08:31,094 --> 00:08:33,096
-Thank you.
-Good.

77
00:08:33,138 --> 00:08:34,639
I could show you around.

78
00:08:34,681 --> 00:08:36,224
That'd be great.
Thank you.

79
00:08:36,266 --> 00:08:38,226
Is there a...
Is there a bank in town?

80
00:08:38,268 --> 00:08:40,561
I'd love to start
an account while I'm here.

81
00:08:41,729 --> 00:08:43,273
[in Italian] Let me do it.

82
00:08:43,315 --> 00:08:45,400
[in English]
Sorry.

83
00:08:45,442 --> 00:08:48,445
-It happens to the best of us.
-Yeah, well... [laughs]

84
00:08:48,487 --> 00:08:51,365
None of our residents
has ever had a local
bank account.

85
00:08:51,406 --> 00:08:52,824
-Really?
-Mmm.

86
00:08:52,866 --> 00:08:54,868
Should I take him
to Montodine?

87
00:08:54,909 --> 00:08:57,204
I think they're closed
for summer vacation.

88
00:08:57,245 --> 00:08:59,289
You try Crema.

89
00:08:59,331 --> 00:09:00,790
Crema?

90
00:09:00,832 --> 00:09:02,709
[speaking other language]
Thank you.

91
00:09:02,750 --> 00:09:04,294
[speaking English]
Is this your orchard?

92
00:09:04,336 --> 00:09:06,213
-[Perlman]
These are Annella's trees.
-[Oliver] Oh, wow.

93
00:09:06,254 --> 00:09:09,341
[Perlman]
Peaches, cherries, apricots...

94
00:09:10,925 --> 00:09:12,219
Pomegranate.

95
00:09:12,260 --> 00:09:13,303
"Melograno."

96
00:09:15,180 --> 00:09:16,390
Mmm.

97
00:09:18,225 --> 00:09:19,976
Have another egg.

98
00:09:20,018 --> 00:09:21,478
Oh, stupid.

99
00:09:21,520 --> 00:09:23,688
No, no, no.
I know myself too well.

100
00:09:23,730 --> 00:09:25,524
If I have a second,
I'm just gonna have a third,
and then a fourth,

101
00:09:25,565 --> 00:09:26,900
and then you're just
gonna have to roll
me out of here.

102
00:09:29,486 --> 00:09:31,405
-Delicious.
-[Annella] Darling?

103
00:09:31,446 --> 00:09:33,198
[Oliver] Thank you.

104
00:09:33,240 --> 00:09:34,908
Shall I give him
Anchise's bike?

105
00:09:43,417 --> 00:09:45,377
[livestock bleating]

106
00:09:45,419 --> 00:09:47,170
[dog barking]

107
00:10:11,570 --> 00:10:14,197
[Oliver] So, what does
one do around here?

108
00:10:14,239 --> 00:10:17,117
Wait for the summer to end.

109
00:10:17,158 --> 00:10:18,410
Yeah?

110
00:10:18,452 --> 00:10:20,078
What do you do
in the winter?

111
00:10:20,120 --> 00:10:22,997
-Wait for summer to come?
-Well, we only come
here for Christmas

112
00:10:23,039 --> 00:10:24,665
and some other vacations.

113
00:10:24,707 --> 00:10:26,126
-Christmas?
I thought you...
-And Easter as well.

114
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:27,668
-Thought you were Jewish.
-Well, we are Jewish,

115
00:10:27,710 --> 00:10:30,004
but also American,
Italian, French.

116
00:10:30,046 --> 00:10:32,299
Somewhat atypical
combination.

117
00:10:33,841 --> 00:10:35,343
Besides my family,
you're probably

118
00:10:35,385 --> 00:10:37,304
the only other Jew
to set foot in this town.

119
00:10:38,513 --> 00:10:39,931
I'm from a small town
in New England.

120
00:10:39,973 --> 00:10:41,558
I know what it's like
to be the odd Jew out.

121
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:43,435
[Elio chuckles]

122
00:10:43,477 --> 00:10:45,437
So, what do you
do around here?

123
00:10:46,729 --> 00:10:48,815
-Just read books.
-[bells chiming]

124
00:10:48,856 --> 00:10:51,985
Transcribe music.
Swim at the river.

125
00:10:52,026 --> 00:10:53,736
-Yeah?
-Go out at night.

126
00:10:53,778 --> 00:10:55,947
-I don't know.
-That sounds fun.

127
00:10:59,742 --> 00:11:01,786
All right, buddy,
thanks for the help.

128
00:11:10,878 --> 00:11:12,589
[Elio] Sorry.
Sorry about that.

129
00:11:12,631 --> 00:11:14,132
It's all right.

130
00:11:14,174 --> 00:11:15,550
All right, later.

131
00:11:26,311 --> 00:11:27,770
[Perlman]
What do you have there?

132
00:11:27,812 --> 00:11:29,814
That should all be...

133
00:11:29,856 --> 00:11:31,232
[laughing]

134
00:11:33,360 --> 00:11:34,986
Oh, what is this?

135
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:39,782
These are the
continuation of these
archaeology department...

136
00:11:39,824 --> 00:11:41,660
[Perlman]
These are archaeology?

137
00:11:41,700 --> 00:11:42,743
[Oliver] Yeah, those are
archaeology. The rest of these
should be history.

138
00:11:42,785 --> 00:11:43,911
[Perlman] Ah, okay.

139
00:11:43,953 --> 00:11:47,165
-More apricot juice?
-[Oliver] Yeah.

140
00:11:47,207 --> 00:11:48,875
-Here, tesoro.
-Thank you.

141
00:11:48,916 --> 00:11:50,335
[in French]
Help yourself, darling.

142
00:11:50,377 --> 00:11:51,670
Thanks.

143
00:11:52,337 --> 00:11:53,963
[piano music playing]

144
00:11:59,802 --> 00:12:02,305
[speaking English]
Help yourself
to some more.

145
00:12:02,347 --> 00:12:06,893
The word "apricot"
comes from the Arabic.

146
00:12:06,934 --> 00:12:10,313
It's like the words
"algebra," "alchemy,"
"alcohol."

147
00:12:10,355 --> 00:12:11,856
It derives from
an Arabic noun

148
00:12:11,898 --> 00:12:13,816
combined with the
Arabic article "al"
before it.

149
00:12:13,858 --> 00:12:17,820
The origin of our
Italian albicocca

150
00:12:17,862 --> 00:12:19,531
is al-barquq.

151
00:12:19,573 --> 00:12:22,325
It's amazing that
today in Israel and
many Arab countries,

152
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:26,538
the fruit's referred to
by a totally different
name, Mismish.

153
00:12:26,580 --> 00:12:28,956
I may have to disagree
with you there, Professor.

154
00:12:28,998 --> 00:12:30,625
Ah?

155
00:12:30,667 --> 00:12:33,545
I'm gonna talk etymology,
so just bear with me
a second. Um...

156
00:12:33,587 --> 00:12:35,171
You're right in the case
that most Latin words

157
00:12:35,213 --> 00:12:37,507
do find their origins
in Greek words.

158
00:12:37,549 --> 00:12:38,799
However, in the case
of "apricot,"

159
00:12:38,841 --> 00:12:40,719
it's a little bit more
of a complicated journey.

160
00:12:40,759 --> 00:12:42,679
Ah. How so?

161
00:12:42,721 --> 00:12:45,348
Well, here, the Greek
actually takes over
from the Latin.

162
00:12:45,390 --> 00:12:48,518
Latin word being,
praecoquum or precoquere.

163
00:12:48,560 --> 00:12:50,353
So it's, "Precook" or,
"Pre-ripen,"as you know.

164
00:12:50,395 --> 00:12:51,605
To be precocious or premature.

165
00:12:52,731 --> 00:12:54,023
And the Byzantines,
to go on,

166
00:12:54,065 --> 00:12:56,943
then borrowed praecox,
which became

167
00:12:56,984 --> 00:12:59,862
prekokkia, which then
became berikokki,

168
00:12:59,904 --> 00:13:02,156
which is how
the Arabs got al-barquq.

169
00:13:13,418 --> 00:13:14,753
That's courtesy
of Philology 101.

170
00:13:15,962 --> 00:13:17,464
Flying colors.

171
00:13:21,217 --> 00:13:22,636
He does this every year.

172
00:13:38,735 --> 00:13:41,195
It's about drink time.
Let's go here.

173
00:13:42,363 --> 00:13:44,407
-[in Italian] Ciao, Romano.
-Ciao, Oliver.

174
00:13:44,449 --> 00:13:47,034
-How are you?
-All good.

175
00:13:51,080 --> 00:13:52,248
[in Italian]

176
00:13:52,290 --> 00:13:53,874
Ciao, boys!

177
00:13:53,916 --> 00:13:55,794
All good?

178
00:13:55,834 --> 00:13:57,545
All good!

179
00:13:57,587 --> 00:13:59,130
[speaking English] Let's see.
What have we got?

180
00:13:59,172 --> 00:14:02,008
-Can you start please?
-Of course!

181
00:14:02,841 --> 00:14:04,885
[indistinct chatter]

182
00:14:22,696 --> 00:14:23,988
[Elio] Good morning, gentlemen.

183
00:14:24,030 --> 00:14:25,740
[all greeting]

184
00:14:28,993 --> 00:14:30,537
How do you know
about this place?

185
00:14:32,664 --> 00:14:34,374
Okay.

186
00:14:34,415 --> 00:14:36,000
[in French] Go, Chiara!

187
00:14:40,004 --> 00:14:41,047
[speaking English]
No, no, no, no, no!

188
00:14:41,088 --> 00:14:42,716
[whooping and clapping]

189
00:14:44,884 --> 00:14:47,387
[in Italian]
He's better than the guy
who came last year.

190
00:14:47,428 --> 00:14:49,263
Remember?

191
00:14:49,305 --> 00:14:50,765
Get in there!

192
00:14:50,807 --> 00:14:53,685
Much better!
See how cute he is.

193
00:14:55,645 --> 00:14:57,731
[indistinct chatter]

194
00:15:05,238 --> 00:15:06,905
Elio, water!

195
00:15:08,241 --> 00:15:09,450
[speaking English]
Perfect timing.

196
00:15:13,329 --> 00:15:15,498
-[Oliver] What's the matter?
Are you all right?
-Huh?

197
00:15:15,540 --> 00:15:17,751
-What, pinch a nerve?
-I'm okay.

198
00:15:17,792 --> 00:15:19,711
Here. Hold this.

199
00:15:19,753 --> 00:15:21,796
Trust me.
I'm about to be a doctor.

200
00:15:21,838 --> 00:15:23,631
Hey, hey, come here.
See? That's the problem.

201
00:15:23,673 --> 00:15:25,132
You're too stressed.

202
00:15:25,174 --> 00:15:27,510
-You just gotta
relax a little bit.
-I am relaxing.

203
00:15:27,552 --> 00:15:29,220
Marzia,
come here for a minute.

204
00:15:30,012 --> 00:15:32,181
Back me up here.

205
00:15:32,223 --> 00:15:33,725
-Feel that. Right there?
-[man] Oliver.

206
00:15:33,767 --> 00:15:34,809
-It's too tight, right?
-Yeah.

207
00:15:34,851 --> 00:15:36,227
-He needs to relax.
-[man] Oliver!

208
00:15:36,269 --> 00:15:37,353
Later.

209
00:15:37,395 --> 00:15:38,937
You should relax more.

210
00:15:41,190 --> 00:15:42,609
Okay, guys, ready?

211
00:15:47,113 --> 00:15:48,155
[whooping]

212
00:15:49,948 --> 00:15:51,951
[Oliver] Okay, our ball,
our ball, our ball.

213
00:15:51,992 --> 00:15:53,411
Twelve serving 11.

214
00:15:54,370 --> 00:15:56,080
Mine, mine, mine, mine.

215
00:15:56,122 --> 00:15:58,291
Go, go, go. Yeah, good.
It's yours, it's yours.

216
00:15:58,833 --> 00:16:00,627
[in Italian]

217
00:16:00,668 --> 00:16:04,255
Sweetheart, Auntie Marcella
and the others are coming
over for dinner.

218
00:16:04,297 --> 00:16:06,883
Is Oliver staying with us
or going out?

219
00:16:06,925 --> 00:16:08,426
Don't know.

220
00:16:09,343 --> 00:16:10,762
What a movie star!

221
00:16:10,804 --> 00:16:13,598
Yes, those Americans...

222
00:16:36,913 --> 00:16:38,832
Sparkling wine!

223
00:16:39,666 --> 00:16:41,041
He's late.

224
00:16:42,418 --> 00:16:44,754
Don't you think...

225
00:16:44,796 --> 00:16:47,882
Don't you think
he's impolite when
he says, "Later"?

226
00:16:48,633 --> 00:16:50,718
Arrogant.

227
00:16:50,760 --> 00:16:53,095
[in English]
I don't think
he's arrogant.

228
00:16:53,137 --> 00:16:54,722
Just watch.

229
00:16:54,764 --> 00:16:56,766
This is how he'll say
good-bye to us when
the time comes.

230
00:16:56,808 --> 00:16:59,059
With his... "Later."

231
00:16:59,101 --> 00:17:00,687
[all laughing]

232
00:17:00,728 --> 00:17:03,105
Meanwhile, we'll have
to put up with him
for six long weeks.

233
00:17:03,147 --> 00:17:05,232
Won't we, darling?

234
00:17:05,984 --> 00:17:07,902
I think he's shy.

235
00:17:07,944 --> 00:17:09,320
You'll grow to like him.

236
00:17:09,362 --> 00:17:10,613
What if I grow to hate him?

237
00:17:10,655 --> 00:17:11,781
[Annella speaking Italian]
Oh, no, sweetheart.

238
00:17:13,992 --> 00:17:16,577
-Take his plates away.
-Very well, madam.

239
00:17:20,038 --> 00:17:21,624
[Annella] Darling?

240
00:17:26,086 --> 00:17:28,548
[indistinct conversation
in Italian]

241
00:17:41,227 --> 00:17:43,813
[speaking English]
Elio, play something.

242
00:17:43,855 --> 00:17:45,565
[in Italian] I don't want to

243
00:17:46,273 --> 00:17:47,400
Why not?

244
00:17:47,441 --> 00:17:49,193
Because I don't want to.

245
00:17:49,235 --> 00:17:51,612
Why don't you go
to Moscazzano with others?

246
00:17:51,654 --> 00:17:53,823
Because I don't want to.

247
00:17:53,865 --> 00:17:55,575
[Annella speaking English]
You're spoiling
everyone's fun.

248
00:17:58,745 --> 00:18:00,580
[low cheering]

249
00:18:04,083 --> 00:18:05,710
Play well, darling.

250
00:18:09,589 --> 00:18:10,798
[sighing]

251
00:18:16,429 --> 00:18:19,599
[playing lively
classical music]

252
00:18:49,087 --> 00:18:51,213
[birds chirping]

253
00:19:00,014 --> 00:19:01,849
[bell tolling]

254
00:19:15,195 --> 00:19:16,405
[blowing]

255
00:19:36,050 --> 00:19:37,384
[knocking on door]

256
00:19:38,803 --> 00:19:40,763
-Hey.
-Hey.

257
00:19:40,805 --> 00:19:42,140
What are you doing?

258
00:19:42,181 --> 00:19:43,390
Reading.

259
00:19:45,018 --> 00:19:46,602
How come you're not
with everyone else
down by the river?

260
00:19:48,562 --> 00:19:51,024
-I have an allergy. It's...
-Yeah, me too.

261
00:19:52,150 --> 00:19:53,484
Maybe we have the same one.

262
00:19:53,526 --> 00:19:54,610
Hmm?

263
00:19:56,696 --> 00:19:58,447
Why don't you and I
go swimming?

264
00:19:58,489 --> 00:20:00,407
-Right now?
-Yeah.

265
00:20:00,449 --> 00:20:02,242
Come on. Let's go.

266
00:20:03,369 --> 00:20:04,954
Do we have
to go right now?

267
00:20:06,164 --> 00:20:07,874
-I'll go get changed.
-Okay.

268
00:20:07,915 --> 00:20:09,416
-Meet you downstairs.
-Mmm-hmm.

269
00:20:28,186 --> 00:20:29,687
See you downstairs.

270
00:20:29,729 --> 00:20:33,191
[door opens and shuts]

271
00:21:04,388 --> 00:21:06,348
Elio, what are you doing?

272
00:21:06,933 --> 00:21:08,684
Reading my music.

273
00:21:08,726 --> 00:21:11,145
No, you're not.

274
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:13,480
-Thinking, then.
-Yeah?

275
00:21:16,525 --> 00:21:17,860
About what?

276
00:21:20,487 --> 00:21:22,448
It's private.

277
00:21:22,489 --> 00:21:23,783
You're not gonna tell me?

278
00:21:23,824 --> 00:21:25,492
I'm not gonna tell you.

279
00:21:25,534 --> 00:21:27,536
He's not gonna tell me
what he's thinking about.

280
00:21:27,578 --> 00:21:28,621
[Annella] Elio.

281
00:21:28,662 --> 00:21:30,497
I guess I'll go hang out
with your mom.

282
00:21:31,540 --> 00:21:33,667
[Oliver] More apricot
juice, please.

283
00:21:35,002 --> 00:21:36,796
[Annella] That's a good boy.

284
00:21:36,837 --> 00:21:38,380
Thank God you're helping me.

285
00:21:49,558 --> 00:21:51,518
[laughter in distance]

286
00:21:51,560 --> 00:21:54,147
[indistinct chatter]

287
00:21:54,188 --> 00:21:56,356
[playing slow tune]

288
00:22:00,569 --> 00:22:03,072
-[Oliver] Sounds nice.
-[stops playing]

289
00:22:03,114 --> 00:22:04,782
[Elio] Thought you
didn't like it.

290
00:22:10,704 --> 00:22:12,165
Play it again, will you?

291
00:22:22,258 --> 00:22:23,259
Follow me.

292
00:22:30,016 --> 00:22:32,852
[indistinct chatter
and laughter]

293
00:22:35,437 --> 00:22:37,648
[plays same tune faster]

294
00:22:55,791 --> 00:22:57,751
That sounds different.
Did you change it?

295
00:22:57,793 --> 00:23:00,629
-Well, I changed it
a little bit.
-Why?

296
00:23:00,671 --> 00:23:02,380
I just played it the way
Liszt would have played it

297
00:23:02,422 --> 00:23:05,176
if he'd altered
Bach's version.

298
00:23:05,218 --> 00:23:06,886
Play that again.

299
00:23:06,927 --> 00:23:09,138
-Play what again?
-The thing
you played outside.

300
00:23:09,180 --> 00:23:11,431
Oh, you want me to play
the thing I played outside?

301
00:23:11,473 --> 00:23:14,643
-Please.
-Ah. [mutters] Of course.

302
00:23:16,187 --> 00:23:18,189
[plays with slight variation]

303
00:23:38,209 --> 00:23:39,793
I can't believe
you changed it again.

304
00:23:39,835 --> 00:23:42,420
-Oh, I changed it a little bit.
-Yeah. Why?

305
00:23:42,462 --> 00:23:44,006
I just played it the way
Busoni would've played it

306
00:23:44,048 --> 00:23:46,259
if he'd altered
Liszt's version.

307
00:23:46,300 --> 00:23:48,468
And what is wrong
with Bach the way
Bach would've played...

308
00:23:48,510 --> 00:23:49,845
Bach never wrote it
for the guitar.

309
00:23:49,887 --> 00:23:51,471
In fact, we're not
even sure Bach
wrote it at all.

310
00:23:51,513 --> 00:23:53,266
Forget I asked.

311
00:23:53,307 --> 00:23:55,309
[plays first tune]

312
00:24:23,670 --> 00:24:25,631
It's young Bach.

313
00:24:25,672 --> 00:24:27,549
He dedicated it
to his brother.

314
00:24:30,552 --> 00:24:33,097
[piano music playing]

315
00:24:59,290 --> 00:25:01,167
[music plays gently
on headphones]

316
00:25:01,208 --> 00:25:02,876
Hey, Professor.

317
00:25:02,918 --> 00:25:04,086
Hello.

318
00:25:04,128 --> 00:25:06,297
Here, please.

319
00:25:06,339 --> 00:25:07,923
I need help.

320
00:25:09,925 --> 00:25:11,051
[Oliver] Just be honest.

321
00:25:11,093 --> 00:25:12,761
How bad is it?

322
00:25:12,803 --> 00:25:16,223
[Perlman] I think
your insights here
are persuasive, but...

323
00:25:16,265 --> 00:25:17,975
-Ciao.
-Ciao.

324
00:25:18,642 --> 00:25:19,893
[in Italian]

325
00:25:19,935 --> 00:25:21,895
Have you been to the river?

326
00:25:22,688 --> 00:25:25,441
[bubbling sounds]

327
00:25:36,243 --> 00:25:38,120
[old man] Mafalda!

328
00:25:38,162 --> 00:25:39,497
Isn't she beautiful?

329
00:25:59,599 --> 00:26:01,643
-[Oliver] Elio.
-Mmm.

330
00:26:01,685 --> 00:26:03,103
[Oliver speaking English]
You sleeping?

331
00:26:04,562 --> 00:26:05,939
I was.

332
00:26:05,981 --> 00:26:08,650
Listen to this drivel.
Tell me what you think.

333
00:26:09,485 --> 00:26:12,238
-Wait.
-What?

334
00:26:12,279 --> 00:26:13,780
Can't hear you.

335
00:26:17,617 --> 00:26:19,245
[groans]

336
00:26:22,831 --> 00:26:24,083
[Oliver] "For the early Greeks,

337
00:26:24,124 --> 00:26:26,252
Heidegger contends,
this underlying hiddenness

338
00:26:26,293 --> 00:26:28,170
is constitutive of
the way beings are,

339
00:26:28,212 --> 00:26:29,505
not only in relation
to themselves

340
00:26:29,547 --> 00:26:32,258
but also in relation
to other entities generally.

341
00:26:32,299 --> 00:26:34,218
In other words, they do not
construe hiddenness

342
00:26:34,260 --> 00:26:37,763
merely or primarily
in terms of entities'
relations to human beings."

343
00:26:39,139 --> 00:26:41,434
Does that make
any sense to you?

344
00:26:41,475 --> 00:26:43,685
Doesn't make
any sense to me.

345
00:26:43,727 --> 00:26:45,687
I don't think
it makes any sense
to your dad, either.

346
00:26:47,189 --> 00:26:48,899
Maybe it did
when you wrote it.

347
00:26:53,695 --> 00:26:57,199
That might be
the kindest thing anybody
has said to me in months.

348
00:26:57,241 --> 00:26:58,409
"Kind?"

349
00:26:59,159 --> 00:27:01,328
Yep. Kind.

350
00:27:07,543 --> 00:27:09,627
♪ Time like silent stares ♪

351
00:27:10,712 --> 00:27:12,089
[indistinct chatter]

352
00:27:12,131 --> 00:27:15,092
♪ With no apology ♪

353
00:27:19,012 --> 00:27:21,432
♪ Move towards the stars ♪

354
00:27:23,809 --> 00:27:26,520
♪ And be my only one ♪

355
00:27:28,481 --> 00:27:30,232
-Hey, Elio.
-Hey.

356
00:27:30,274 --> 00:27:31,691
Hey!

357
00:27:31,733 --> 00:27:33,360
[song continues playing]

358
00:27:33,402 --> 00:27:34,445
[in Italian]

359
00:27:34,487 --> 00:27:35,653
Come here.

360
00:27:37,990 --> 00:27:39,450
What's going on?

361
00:27:39,492 --> 00:27:41,368
Is he trying to
get it on with her?

362
00:27:41,410 --> 00:27:43,537
Elio, he already succeeded?

363
00:27:45,456 --> 00:27:46,915
What do I know?

364
00:27:46,957 --> 00:27:48,666
I'd love to be
in his shoes.

365
00:27:48,708 --> 00:27:50,628
Who wouldn't love
to be in her shoes?

366
00:27:53,088 --> 00:27:55,341
She wants him,
no matter what!

367
00:27:56,383 --> 00:28:00,513
♪ Lady, lady, lady, lady ♪

368
00:28:01,847 --> 00:28:05,851
♪ Don't walk
this lonely avenue ♪

369
00:28:07,478 --> 00:28:11,982
♪ Oh, lady, lady, lady, lady ♪

370
00:28:12,024 --> 00:28:15,110
♪ Let me touch
that part of you ♪

371
00:28:15,819 --> 00:28:18,989
♪ You want me to ♪

372
00:28:30,083 --> 00:28:31,627
["Love my way" playing]

373
00:28:39,593 --> 00:28:40,760
Coming?

374
00:28:43,096 --> 00:28:44,431
I'll come later.

375
00:28:45,723 --> 00:28:48,727
[excited screeching]

376
00:28:48,768 --> 00:28:51,980
♪ A kiss is not enough ♪

377
00:28:54,816 --> 00:28:57,903
♪ Love my way ♪

378
00:28:57,944 --> 00:29:00,739
♪ It's a new road ♪

379
00:29:02,616 --> 00:29:05,703
♪ I follow ♪

380
00:29:05,743 --> 00:29:08,664
♪ Where my mind goes ♪

381
00:29:08,706 --> 00:29:11,833
♪ They'd put us
on a railroad ♪

382
00:29:11,875 --> 00:29:15,087
♪ They'd dearly make us pay ♪

383
00:29:16,046 --> 00:29:19,758
♪ For laughing in their faces ♪

384
00:29:19,799 --> 00:29:22,511
♪ And making it our way ♪

385
00:29:25,389 --> 00:29:30,894
♪ Love my way
It's a new road ♪

386
00:29:33,146 --> 00:29:38,694
♪ I follow
Where my mind goes ♪

387
00:29:40,820 --> 00:29:43,781
♪ Love my way ♪

388
00:29:43,823 --> 00:29:46,452
♪ It's a new road ♪

389
00:29:48,537 --> 00:29:51,957
♪ I follow ♪

390
00:29:51,998 --> 00:29:54,460
♪ Where my mind goes ♪

391
00:29:58,589 --> 00:29:59,965
[in French]

392
00:30:00,006 --> 00:30:02,760
Are you mad with me because
you are mad with Chiara?

393
00:30:02,800 --> 00:30:04,470
Why would I be
mad at Chiara?

394
00:30:05,679 --> 00:30:07,222
Because of him.

395
00:30:07,264 --> 00:30:08,724
Because of who?

396
00:30:09,891 --> 00:30:11,143
Of Oliver.

397
00:30:22,655 --> 00:30:24,030
Turn around.

398
00:30:38,671 --> 00:30:40,506
Meet me here tomorrow night?

399
00:30:42,424 --> 00:30:44,343
[screaming, splashing]

400
00:30:47,387 --> 00:30:49,723
Wait for me!

401
00:30:49,765 --> 00:30:51,308
Come on.

402
00:31:05,113 --> 00:31:06,865
[speaking English]
We almost had sex
last night...

403
00:31:06,906 --> 00:31:08,492
Marzia and me.

404
00:31:09,618 --> 00:31:12,037
Hmm? Well, why didn't you?

405
00:31:13,330 --> 00:31:16,082
I don't know.

406
00:31:16,124 --> 00:31:18,876
Well, you know,
it's better to have
tried and failed, right?

407
00:31:18,918 --> 00:31:22,756
All I had to do
was find the courage
to reach out and touch.

408
00:31:22,798 --> 00:31:24,383
She would have said yes.

409
00:31:24,424 --> 00:31:25,967
Well, try again later.

410
00:31:26,009 --> 00:31:28,094
Try what later?

411
00:31:28,136 --> 00:31:29,847
I just heard from
the people in Sirmione.

412
00:31:29,887 --> 00:31:31,640
They say they've
come up with something.

413
00:31:31,682 --> 00:31:33,933
Oh! Fantastic.

414
00:31:33,975 --> 00:31:35,644
Going there today.

415
00:31:35,686 --> 00:31:38,146
-Would you like to come along?
-I would love to.
Thank you.

416
00:31:39,939 --> 00:31:41,775
-[Annella] Smell this.
-Can I come, too?

417
00:31:41,817 --> 00:31:44,986
Ah, on the condition
you remain silent.

418
00:31:45,028 --> 00:31:46,363
Silent as in,
"He has too many opinions,"

419
00:31:46,405 --> 00:31:48,031
or silent as in,
"Just not telling anybody

420
00:31:48,073 --> 00:31:49,783
what an amazing
thing you've dug up"?

421
00:31:49,825 --> 00:31:51,410
Well, nothing
has been dug up.

422
00:31:51,451 --> 00:31:54,413
It's what has
been brought out,
out of the water.

423
00:31:54,454 --> 00:31:55,539
[cycle bell rings]

424
00:31:56,623 --> 00:31:58,124
Ciao, Chiara!

425
00:32:01,461 --> 00:32:02,796
[in French]

426
00:32:02,838 --> 00:32:04,381
What are you doing?

427
00:32:04,423 --> 00:32:06,216
Going to Lake Garda
with my dad.

428
00:32:06,258 --> 00:32:09,177
He wants to show Oliver
where he's dredging.

429
00:32:09,219 --> 00:32:11,680
Can you tell him
I came by?

430
00:32:11,722 --> 00:32:13,599
He's inside with my dad,
helping him.

431
00:32:15,434 --> 00:32:18,771
You were amazing last night,
on the dance floor.

432
00:32:18,812 --> 00:32:20,814
-He's a good dancer.
-A good dancer.

433
00:32:23,024 --> 00:32:24,860
He's good-looking, too.

434
00:32:26,194 --> 00:32:28,405
-Want to get us together?
-No.

435
00:32:28,447 --> 00:32:29,823
[chuckles]

436
00:32:29,865 --> 00:32:31,533
Come in.

437
00:32:48,675 --> 00:32:50,719
[indistinct conversation]

438
00:33:08,278 --> 00:33:10,864
[speaking English]
Dad always sits up front
with Anchise to navigate.

439
00:33:12,783 --> 00:33:14,242
[cycle bell dings]

440
00:33:18,413 --> 00:33:20,916
She seems to
like you a lot.

441
00:33:20,958 --> 00:33:23,627
She's more beautiful
than she was last year.

442
00:33:25,044 --> 00:33:27,756
I saw her naked
on a night swim once.

443
00:33:28,590 --> 00:33:30,676
Great body.

444
00:33:30,717 --> 00:33:32,177
Trying to get me
to like her?

445
00:33:32,218 --> 00:33:34,304
What would be
the harm in that?

446
00:33:34,346 --> 00:33:36,139
No, no harm.

447
00:33:36,181 --> 00:33:38,558
Just typically like to go
at those things on my own,
if you don't mind.

448
00:33:44,063 --> 00:33:45,774
[speaking other language]
I'll drive today!

449
00:33:48,443 --> 00:33:50,445
Just don't play
at being the good host.

450
00:33:52,322 --> 00:33:55,742
[Perlman] Anchise,
take the afternoon off.

451
00:33:58,411 --> 00:34:00,789
[speaking English]
What's going on, boys?

452
00:34:00,831 --> 00:34:06,169
Oliver, come.
Sit up front.
Be my navigator.

453
00:34:06,211 --> 00:34:08,630
What? What?

454
00:34:08,672 --> 00:34:10,007
[engine revs]

455
00:34:11,884 --> 00:34:14,011
[distant chatter]

456
00:34:23,729 --> 00:34:25,814
-[laughing] Dr. Roseburg.
-Samuel!

457
00:34:25,856 --> 00:34:27,273
[Rosenberg] Benvenuto.
[Perlman] Look who's here.

458
00:34:29,609 --> 00:34:31,361
He's grown a bit, eh?
And this is Oliver.

459
00:34:43,790 --> 00:34:44,791
[Teresa] Ciao.

460
00:34:45,375 --> 00:34:47,335
Ciao, Teresa.

461
00:34:49,254 --> 00:34:50,547
[Perlman] Oh!

462
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:52,632
Ah.

463
00:34:59,681 --> 00:35:00,849
[in Italian]

464
00:35:00,891 --> 00:35:02,893
[Rosenberg]
Sammy! Come on!

465
00:35:15,697 --> 00:35:17,156
Truce?

466
00:35:18,951 --> 00:35:20,619
[Perlman speaking English]
Hey, boys.

467
00:35:26,165 --> 00:35:31,463
[Perlman] The ship went down
in 1827 on the way to Isola
del Garda.

468
00:35:31,504 --> 00:35:35,258
Gossip has it this statue
was a gift from Count Lechi

469
00:35:35,300 --> 00:35:38,637
to his lover, contralto
Adelaide Malanotte.

470
00:35:41,264 --> 00:35:43,516
There are four known sets,

471
00:35:43,558 --> 00:35:45,518
after the Praxiteles
originals.

472
00:35:45,560 --> 00:35:47,353
This fellow's at number three.

473
00:35:47,395 --> 00:35:50,023
The Emperor Hadrian
had a pair, dug up at Tivoli,

474
00:35:50,065 --> 00:35:54,027
but one of the more
philistine of the Farnese
Popes melted them down

475
00:35:54,069 --> 00:35:57,906
and had them recast
as a particularly
voluptuous Venus.

476
00:36:18,468 --> 00:36:21,930
Who'd like to go for a swim
before we head back?

477
00:36:21,972 --> 00:36:26,893
We're all such pros.
If I got my own statue,
it would probably be on there.

478
00:36:28,478 --> 00:36:30,355
[whooping]

479
00:36:34,067 --> 00:36:35,735
[Oliver] Elio!

480
00:36:35,777 --> 00:36:37,278
[Elio] Oliver!

481
00:36:41,074 --> 00:36:43,118
-[Elio] I have to go.
I have to go.
-Hey! Hey!

482
00:36:43,160 --> 00:36:44,870
I have to go.

483
00:36:46,538 --> 00:36:48,206
Goodness.

484
00:36:52,002 --> 00:36:54,337
-Are you going, too?
-No, no.

485
00:36:54,379 --> 00:36:56,506
I should stay and do
some work on my book.

486
00:36:56,548 --> 00:36:59,885
Come on. How about a drink
to celebrate the day?

487
00:36:59,926 --> 00:37:02,012
-Okay, maybe just one.
-All right!

488
00:37:08,267 --> 00:37:09,686
[crickets chirping]

489
00:37:13,690 --> 00:37:14,900
Marzia?

490
00:37:20,780 --> 00:37:22,782
[birds chirping]

491
00:37:39,925 --> 00:37:42,385
[playing piano softly]

492
00:38:19,798 --> 00:38:22,759
The Cosmic Fragments
by Heraclitus.

493
00:38:30,976 --> 00:38:34,271
[Oliver] The meaning
of the river flowing is not
that all things are changing

494
00:38:34,311 --> 00:38:36,355
so that we cannot
encounter them twice,

495
00:38:36,397 --> 00:38:39,525
but that some things stay
the same only by changing.

496
00:39:01,673 --> 00:39:03,008
[footsteps approaching]

497
00:39:12,851 --> 00:39:13,852
[knock on door]

498
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:25,446
-[knock on door]
-Mmm.

499
00:39:27,406 --> 00:39:30,202
[speaking other language]
Sorry, Elio. I brought
some clean clothes.

500
00:39:30,243 --> 00:39:31,286
Mmm.

501
00:39:35,248 --> 00:39:36,708
Leave the door open.

502
00:39:37,834 --> 00:39:39,502
-Thanks.
-You're welcome.

503
00:39:41,462 --> 00:39:43,422
[fly buzzing]

504
00:41:19,894 --> 00:41:21,478
[voices in distance]

505
00:42:16,326 --> 00:42:18,411
[thunder rumbling]

506
00:42:21,539 --> 00:42:23,541
[rain pattering]

507
00:42:28,296 --> 00:42:30,215
[Annella speaking English]
Darling, have you
seen my Heptaméron?

508
00:42:33,343 --> 00:42:34,469
Mafalda.

509
00:42:39,307 --> 00:42:40,766
It's in German.

510
00:42:43,395 --> 00:42:44,437
Okay.

511
00:42:46,772 --> 00:42:50,568
I can't remember where
we left off, but I think
you'll like this one.

512
00:42:53,821 --> 00:42:55,740
Come here, darling.

513
00:42:57,700 --> 00:42:59,494
So, I'll translate, huh?

514
00:43:02,121 --> 00:43:03,540
[reading German]

515
00:43:08,753 --> 00:43:10,463
[in English]
"A handsome young knight

516
00:43:10,505 --> 00:43:13,049
is madly in love
with a princess.

517
00:43:13,091 --> 00:43:15,009
And she, too,
is in love with him,

518
00:43:16,344 --> 00:43:19,722
though she seems not to be
entirely aware of it.

519
00:43:20,765 --> 00:43:22,850
Despite the friendship..."

520
00:43:22,892 --> 00:43:24,936
[reads softly]

521
00:43:24,977 --> 00:43:29,107
"...that blossoms
between them,

522
00:43:29,148 --> 00:43:32,026
or perhaps because of
that very friendship,

523
00:43:33,236 --> 00:43:35,821
the young knight
finds himself so..."

524
00:43:35,863 --> 00:43:37,782
[reads softly]

525
00:43:38,824 --> 00:43:42,036
"...so humbled
and speechless

526
00:43:42,078 --> 00:43:47,041
that he's totally unable
to bring up the subject
of his love.

527
00:43:47,083 --> 00:43:50,795
Till one day,
he asks the princess
point-blank..."

528
00:43:52,004 --> 00:43:53,714
[reads softly in German]

529
00:44:02,140 --> 00:44:04,309
"Is it better
to speak or to die?"

530
00:44:09,688 --> 00:44:12,733
I'd never have the courage
to ask a question like that.

531
00:44:14,319 --> 00:44:15,570
I doubt that.

532
00:44:20,325 --> 00:44:22,701
Hey, Elly-Belly.

533
00:44:24,496 --> 00:44:26,664
You do know that
you can always talk to us.

534
00:44:29,125 --> 00:44:31,252
[birds chirping]

535
00:44:33,338 --> 00:44:36,508
[Elio] My mom's been
reading this 16th-century
French romance.

536
00:44:36,549 --> 00:44:39,636
She read some of it
to my dad and I the day
the lights went out.

537
00:44:39,677 --> 00:44:42,305
[Oliver] Yeah, about
the knight that doesn't know
whether to speak or die?

538
00:44:42,347 --> 00:44:43,431
[Elio] Right.

539
00:44:44,599 --> 00:44:46,100
[Oliver] So,
does he or doesn't he?

540
00:44:48,102 --> 00:44:49,895
"Better to speak,"
she said.

541
00:44:51,856 --> 00:44:53,608
But she's on her guard.

542
00:44:54,984 --> 00:44:56,902
She senses a trap somewhere.

543
00:45:03,868 --> 00:45:05,161
So, does he speak?

544
00:45:06,412 --> 00:45:07,497
No.

545
00:45:09,790 --> 00:45:11,876
-He fudges.
-Hmm.

546
00:45:13,002 --> 00:45:14,212
It figures.

547
00:45:14,253 --> 00:45:15,380
He's French.

548
00:45:21,636 --> 00:45:24,055
I gotta go to town
in a little bit to pick
some things up.

549
00:45:24,096 --> 00:45:27,058
Oh, I can go. I'm not
doing anything today.

550
00:45:28,767 --> 00:45:30,269
Then why don't
we go together?

551
00:45:30,311 --> 00:45:31,604
Right now?

552
00:45:31,646 --> 00:45:34,899
Yeah. Right now.

553
00:45:34,940 --> 00:45:37,360
That is, of course,
unless you have more
important business going on.

554
00:45:37,402 --> 00:45:39,736
[mock imitation]

555
00:45:52,083 --> 00:45:53,125
Mind if I put
this in your bag?

556
00:45:53,167 --> 00:45:54,168
Yes, please.

557
00:46:04,178 --> 00:46:05,471
[in Italian]

558
00:46:05,513 --> 00:46:07,306
I straightened the wheels
and inflated the tires.

559
00:46:07,348 --> 00:46:08,765
Perfect. Thanks.

560
00:46:10,935 --> 00:46:12,645
[speaking English] I fell.

561
00:46:12,687 --> 00:46:15,565
I was coming home
the other day, and I scraped
myself pretty badly.

562
00:46:15,607 --> 00:46:18,401
Anchise insisted
on applying some sort
of witches' brew.

563
00:46:18,443 --> 00:46:19,818
I think it helped.

564
00:46:20,486 --> 00:46:21,778
[gasps]

565
00:46:30,162 --> 00:46:32,582
[cows mooing]

566
00:46:44,176 --> 00:46:45,553
Hold this for a second,
will you?

567
00:47:05,364 --> 00:47:06,699
-Want one?
-Sure.

568
00:47:31,641 --> 00:47:32,725
Not bad, huh?

569
00:47:33,518 --> 00:47:34,644
Not bad at all.

570
00:47:37,689 --> 00:47:38,981
I thought
you didn't smoke.

571
00:47:40,608 --> 00:47:41,693
I don't.

572
00:47:47,281 --> 00:47:51,076
-So, World War II, huh?
-No. This is World War I.

573
00:47:51,118 --> 00:47:53,579
You'd have to be
at least 80 years old
to have known any of them.

574
00:47:54,747 --> 00:47:56,873
I never even heard
of the Battle of Piave.

575
00:47:56,915 --> 00:47:59,544
Battle of Piave was one
of the most lethal battles
of World War I.

576
00:48:00,211 --> 00:48:01,920
170,000 people died.

577
00:48:03,464 --> 00:48:05,299
Is there anything
you don't know?

578
00:48:09,094 --> 00:48:10,596
I know nothing, Oliver.

579
00:48:15,810 --> 00:48:17,645
Well, you seem to know
more than anybody else
around here.

580
00:48:17,687 --> 00:48:20,022
Well, if you only knew
how little I know about
the things that matter.

581
00:48:23,275 --> 00:48:24,652
What things that matter?

582
00:48:31,950 --> 00:48:33,327
You know what things.

583
00:48:40,292 --> 00:48:41,627
Why are you
telling me this?

584
00:48:46,006 --> 00:48:47,258
'Cause I thought
you should know.

585
00:48:49,093 --> 00:48:51,470
Because you thought
I should know?

586
00:48:53,723 --> 00:48:55,140
'Cause I wanted
you to know?

587
00:48:58,603 --> 00:49:00,897
Because I wanted you to know.

588
00:49:04,650 --> 00:49:06,402
Because I wanted you to know.

589
00:49:11,657 --> 00:49:13,618
'Cause I wanted
you to know.

590
00:49:24,545 --> 00:49:27,381
Because there's no one else
I can say this to but you.

591
00:49:34,012 --> 00:49:35,807
Are you saying
what I think
you're saying?

592
00:49:43,522 --> 00:49:46,983
Don't go anywhere.
Stay right here.

593
00:49:47,025 --> 00:49:48,653
You know I'm not
going anywhere.

594
00:50:18,098 --> 00:50:19,684
They mixed up
all of my pages.

595
00:50:19,725 --> 00:50:22,311
I'm gonna have to
retype this whole thing.

596
00:50:22,353 --> 00:50:23,855
I'm not gonna have
anything to work on
this afternoon.

597
00:50:23,896 --> 00:50:25,397
-This is gonna set me
back a whole day.
-[bell chiming]

598
00:50:26,190 --> 00:50:28,609
Damn it.

599
00:50:28,651 --> 00:50:30,486
I shouldn't have
said anything.

600
00:50:30,528 --> 00:50:32,112
Just pretend
you never did.

601
00:50:32,154 --> 00:50:34,239
What does that mean?
We're on speaking
terms, but not really?

602
00:50:37,785 --> 00:50:40,036
It means, we can't
talk about those
kinds of things

603
00:50:41,163 --> 00:50:42,414
Okay?

604
00:50:44,124 --> 00:50:46,042
We just can't.

605
00:51:00,599 --> 00:51:01,642
Hey!

606
00:51:01,684 --> 00:51:02,601
[in Italian]

607
00:51:02,643 --> 00:51:04,896
Let's go, American!

608
00:51:08,649 --> 00:51:10,150
[panting]

609
00:51:25,499 --> 00:51:27,001
-[speaking English] Ready?
-Let's go.

610
00:52:02,787 --> 00:52:03,955
Pretty much.

611
00:52:14,256 --> 00:52:16,050
-You thirsty?
-Yeah.

612
00:52:17,009 --> 00:52:18,052
[in Italian]

613
00:52:18,094 --> 00:52:19,887
Good morning, ma'am.

614
00:52:21,055 --> 00:52:23,139
Excuse me.

615
00:52:23,181 --> 00:52:26,268
Could I ask
for a glass of water?

616
00:52:33,901 --> 00:52:35,027
[Oliver chuckles]

617
00:52:36,737 --> 00:52:38,238
Il Duce.

618
00:52:38,280 --> 00:52:39,907
"People of Italy"

619
00:52:41,366 --> 00:52:42,701
That's Italy.

620
00:52:46,497 --> 00:52:48,415
-Thank you.
-You're welcome.

621
00:53:26,871 --> 00:53:27,913
[speaking English] Come on.

622
00:53:49,852 --> 00:53:52,646
This is my spot.
It's all mine.

623
00:53:54,398 --> 00:53:57,193
I come here to read.

624
00:53:57,233 --> 00:53:59,444
I can't tell you
the number of books
I've read here.

625
00:54:01,947 --> 00:54:04,116
Oh, my God.
It's freezing.

626
00:54:05,241 --> 00:54:07,161
The spring
is in the mountains.

627
00:54:07,745 --> 00:54:09,163
The Alpi Orobie.

628
00:54:10,497 --> 00:54:11,874
The water comes
straight down from there.

629
00:54:38,025 --> 00:54:40,236
[Oliver] I like
the way you say things.

630
00:54:40,276 --> 00:54:42,780
I don't know why
you're always putting
yourself down, though.

631
00:54:42,821 --> 00:54:45,157
[Elio] So you won't,
I guess?

632
00:54:49,078 --> 00:54:50,913
You really that afraid
of what I think?

633
00:55:01,339 --> 00:55:04,176
[both chuckle]

634
00:55:04,218 --> 00:55:06,011
[Oliver] You're making things
very difficult for me.

635
00:55:14,561 --> 00:55:16,021
[sighs]

636
00:55:18,649 --> 00:55:20,525
I love this, Oliver.

637
00:55:22,027 --> 00:55:23,821
[sighs]

638
00:55:26,073 --> 00:55:27,283
What?

639
00:55:31,495 --> 00:55:32,621
Everything.

640
00:55:33,455 --> 00:55:34,999
[chuckles]

641
00:55:37,668 --> 00:55:39,044
Us, you mean?

642
00:55:40,712 --> 00:55:42,298
Eh, it's not bad.

643
00:55:43,257 --> 00:55:44,300
It's not bad.

644
00:56:35,391 --> 00:56:36,894
[sighing]

645
00:56:39,271 --> 00:56:40,356
Better now?

646
00:56:47,403 --> 00:56:48,780
Mmm-mmm.

647
00:56:48,822 --> 00:56:51,075
No, no, no.

648
00:56:52,076 --> 00:56:54,203
-We should go.
-Why?

649
00:56:54,245 --> 00:56:57,122
I know myself. Okay?
And we've been good.

650
00:56:57,164 --> 00:56:58,623
We haven't done anything
to be ashamed of,

651
00:56:58,665 --> 00:56:59,791
and that's a good thing.

652
00:57:00,500 --> 00:57:01,668
I wanna be good.

653
00:57:02,336 --> 00:57:03,337
Okay?

654
00:57:10,261 --> 00:57:11,970
Am I offending you?

655
00:57:18,852 --> 00:57:20,020
Just don't.

656
00:57:27,152 --> 00:57:29,321
I think it's starting
to get infected.

657
00:57:31,240 --> 00:57:32,908
We can stop by
the pharmacist's
on the way back.

658
00:57:33,533 --> 00:57:34,826
Excellent idea.

659
00:57:42,000 --> 00:57:45,587
[in Italian]
So we got the government
of Bettino Craxi...

660
00:57:45,629 --> 00:57:48,215
Because we don't do anything
but talk, talk, talk.

661
00:57:48,257 --> 00:57:50,217
Let me speak.

662
00:57:50,259 --> 00:57:53,804
We have five parties
that do nothing but fight.

663
00:57:53,845 --> 00:57:56,765
Smoke and shut up!
Let them speak, him, her.

664
00:57:56,807 --> 00:57:59,684
I'd like to know
what they think too.

665
00:57:59,726 --> 00:58:02,604
Annella, what do you think?
A five party government!

666
00:58:02,646 --> 00:58:05,857
Darling, I think
it's the historic
compromise...

667
00:58:05,899 --> 00:58:10,028
Don't say that.
Compromises are tragic.

668
00:58:10,070 --> 00:58:12,948
You've changed since
you inherited this place.

669
00:58:12,990 --> 00:58:14,699
What's that got
to do with it?

670
00:58:14,741 --> 00:58:16,534
What are you saying?

671
00:58:17,244 --> 00:58:18,912
You're mad, darling.

672
00:58:19,746 --> 00:58:21,081
You asshole!

673
00:58:21,123 --> 00:58:24,918
-She's right.
-And you don't say
anything to her.

674
00:58:25,543 --> 00:58:27,421
Say something.

675
00:58:27,463 --> 00:58:29,547
You're resigned.

676
00:58:29,589 --> 00:58:32,176
Why don't we talk
about the death of Bunuel?

677
00:58:32,217 --> 00:58:35,262
Bunuel was a genius

678
00:58:35,304 --> 00:58:36,888
-Know him?
-Cinema isn't the answer.

679
00:58:36,930 --> 00:58:40,476
Cinema is a mirror
of reality and it's a filter.

680
00:58:40,516 --> 00:58:44,146
They broadcast
The Phantom of Liberty
with constant interr...

681
00:58:44,188 --> 00:58:46,731
Everyone loves Bunuel

682
00:58:46,773 --> 00:58:48,442
Let's hear his opinion

683
00:58:48,484 --> 00:58:51,028
He doesn't know
anything about Italy!

684
00:58:51,069 --> 00:58:53,113
Say something.
Give us your impression.

685
00:58:53,155 --> 00:58:54,739
Do you have an impression?

686
00:58:54,781 --> 00:58:56,908
Darling, he's American.

687
00:58:56,950 --> 00:58:58,285
That doesn't mean stupid!

688
00:59:02,956 --> 00:59:04,249
[laughing]

689
00:59:04,291 --> 00:59:06,418
Just stop.

690
00:59:06,460 --> 00:59:10,422
I don't give an easy ride
to some politicians.

691
00:59:10,464 --> 00:59:13,425
She didn't say that.

692
00:59:13,467 --> 00:59:15,386
I'm going to go mad.

693
00:59:15,427 --> 00:59:17,262
What's the matter?

694
00:59:18,514 --> 00:59:20,349
What's wrong?

695
00:59:20,391 --> 00:59:22,518
It's nothing.
It happens all the time.

696
00:59:22,559 --> 00:59:25,854
-Mafalda, ice?
-It's in the fridge.

697
00:59:25,896 --> 00:59:28,440
You get used to
absolutely everything.

698
01:00:04,893 --> 01:00:08,146
Don't you realize
you're mixing everything up?

699
01:00:08,188 --> 01:00:10,190
What are you
talking about?

700
01:00:10,232 --> 01:00:12,568
-There's no more
politics, nothing.
-He's left too.

701
01:00:14,027 --> 01:00:15,446
[softly] Elio.

702
01:00:19,241 --> 01:00:20,867
Elio?

703
01:00:20,909 --> 01:00:22,160
[speaking English]
You all right?

704
01:00:23,370 --> 01:00:24,621
Sit for a second.

705
01:00:27,040 --> 01:00:28,208
If you insist...

706
01:00:32,670 --> 01:00:34,423
That wasn't my fault, right?

707
01:00:34,465 --> 01:00:35,591
No.

708
01:00:37,509 --> 01:00:38,885
I'm a mess.

709
01:00:42,222 --> 01:00:45,225
Well, the kitchen
table sure is.

710
01:00:48,145 --> 01:00:49,313
[winces]

711
01:00:50,772 --> 01:00:53,317
Ow! Where'd you
learn to do that?

712
01:00:53,358 --> 01:00:56,194
My bubby used to
do this for us
when we were sick.

713
01:00:56,236 --> 01:00:57,821
Trust me, it helps.

714
01:01:02,784 --> 01:01:04,620
I used to have
one of these.

715
01:01:04,661 --> 01:01:06,830
-You used to?
-Yeah.

716
01:01:06,871 --> 01:01:08,706
How come you
never wear it?

717
01:01:08,748 --> 01:01:11,502
My mother says
we are Jews of discretion.

718
01:01:12,210 --> 01:01:13,211
Well...

719
01:01:14,421 --> 01:01:16,298
I guess that works
for your mother.

720
01:01:17,341 --> 01:01:18,716
Funny witch.

721
01:01:19,593 --> 01:01:21,261
[both laughing]

722
01:01:22,804 --> 01:01:24,139
[groaning]

723
01:01:24,181 --> 01:01:26,266
Fuck, you'll kill me
if you do that.

724
01:01:26,308 --> 01:01:28,143
I hope not.

725
01:01:34,232 --> 01:01:36,234
[laughing] Ciao.

726
01:01:38,612 --> 01:01:40,197
Hey, are you leaving?

727
01:01:40,238 --> 01:01:42,073
-Where's Elio?
-He's inside.

728
01:01:42,115 --> 01:01:44,368
He had a bit of
a nosebleed during lunch,
and he's just resting.

729
01:01:44,409 --> 01:01:46,119
-Really?
-Yeah.

730
01:01:46,161 --> 01:01:47,829
-Okay. I'll be
back in a minute.
-Bye.

731
01:01:47,871 --> 01:01:49,498
Don't go anywhere.

732
01:02:00,884 --> 01:02:01,926
[in French]

733
01:02:01,968 --> 01:02:02,969
You okay?

734
01:02:10,726 --> 01:02:12,062
Are we going out?

735
01:02:13,855 --> 01:02:17,526
I don't know if I can go out.
If my mom sees, she'll worry.

736
01:02:17,568 --> 01:02:19,611
-She will?
-Yeah, she's a pain.

737
01:02:25,033 --> 01:02:26,535
Where's Oliver?

738
01:02:26,577 --> 01:02:28,119
[chuckles] Don't ask me.

739
01:02:31,873 --> 01:02:33,791
[laughing, chatting]

740
01:02:45,679 --> 01:02:48,098
Where's Oliver?

741
01:02:48,139 --> 01:02:50,934
-Didn't he go out?
-Would you like
a smoothie?

742
01:02:50,975 --> 01:02:53,604
No, thank you.
We're having dinner soon.

743
01:02:53,645 --> 01:02:55,021
All right.

744
01:02:55,063 --> 01:02:56,481
I'm going out tonight.

745
01:02:56,523 --> 01:02:59,817
-Don't make me worry.
-What are you
talking about?

746
01:02:59,859 --> 01:03:01,612
This is no good, madam.

747
01:03:01,653 --> 01:03:03,821
-Let him do
his own thing.
-Fine.

748
01:03:03,863 --> 01:03:05,990
Why's she hassling me?
I'm 17.

749
01:03:06,032 --> 01:03:07,576
She's worried
about you.

750
01:03:12,372 --> 01:03:14,874
You like him,
don't you? Oliver?

751
01:03:15,875 --> 01:03:18,253
Everyone likes Oliver.

752
01:03:18,295 --> 01:03:20,297
I think he likes you, too.

753
01:03:20,338 --> 01:03:21,590
More than you do.

754
01:03:24,134 --> 01:03:26,177
Is that your impression?

755
01:03:26,219 --> 01:03:29,055
-No, he told me.
-When did he say that?

756
01:03:30,056 --> 01:03:31,433
A while ago.

757
01:03:54,872 --> 01:03:55,915
[in Italian]

758
01:03:55,957 --> 01:03:58,293
Mafalda, do you know
where Oliver is?

759
01:03:58,335 --> 01:03:59,795
I have no idea.

760
01:04:03,548 --> 01:04:05,258
♪ It's been a long, long time ♪

761
01:04:05,300 --> 01:04:08,804
♪ Since I've memorized
your face ♪

762
01:04:10,263 --> 01:04:12,056
♪ It's been four hours now ♪

763
01:04:12,098 --> 01:04:15,602
♪ Since I've wandered
through your place ♪

764
01:04:17,103 --> 01:04:19,356
♪ And when I sleep
on your couch ♪

765
01:04:19,397 --> 01:04:22,150
♪ I feel very safe ♪

766
01:04:23,985 --> 01:04:26,112
♪ And when you bring
the blankets ♪

767
01:04:26,154 --> 01:04:29,491
♪ I cover up my face ♪

768
01:04:29,533 --> 01:04:31,368
♪ I do ♪

769
01:04:32,828 --> 01:04:36,247
♪ Love you ♪

770
01:04:36,289 --> 01:04:38,124
♪ I do ♪

771
01:04:39,751 --> 01:04:43,087
♪ Love you ♪

772
01:04:58,228 --> 01:05:00,230
♪ And when you play guitar ♪

773
